In article <1cjrskINNd2@gap.caltech.edu>, hal@cco (Hal Finney) writes:
>I also think it's interesting that these proposals appear just as public-
>key cryptography is starting to become widespread, with the forthcoming
>release of PEM, and such packages as Riordan's RIPEM and Zimmermann's PGP
>starting to spread.  The government never tried to get us to "escrow" our
>DES keys, for some reason.  Maybe they didn't need to; maybe the rumors
>that the government could break DES were true all along.  Otherwise why
>is this idea appearing now instead of fifteen years ago?

Perhaps because with DES as such, key distribution was difficult
enough to make it hard to use by masses?  With tools like PGP this is
changing and key distribution is easy.

